Here's the proper approach using MAUI's app lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**In your `NotePage.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public partial class NotePage : ContentPage
{
    private const string DraftKey = "note_draft";

    public NotePage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        // Restore draft on page creation
        NoteEditor.Text = Preferences.Get(DraftKey, string.Empty);
    }

    protected override void OnAppearing()
    {
        base.OnAppearing();
        // Subscribe to lifecycle events
        App.Current.Windows[0].Deactivated += OnAppBackgrounded;
        App.Current.Windows[0].Activated += OnAppResumed;
    }

    protected override void OnDisappearing()
    {
        base.OnDisappearing();
        App.Current.Windows[0].Deactivated -= OnAppBackgrounded;
        App.Current.Windows[0].Activated -= OnAppResumed;
    }

    private void OnAppBackgrounded(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        // Save draft when app goes to background
        Preferences.Set(DraftKey, NoteEditor.Text ?? string.Empty);
    }

    private void OnAppResumed(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        // Optionally refresh from saved state
        NoteEditor.Text = Preferences.Get(DraftKey, string.Empty);
    }

    public void ClearDraft()
    {
        // Call this after the user explicitly saves their note
        Preferences.Remove(DraftKey);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`Window.Deactivated`** fires when the app goes to background — save here.
- **`Window.Activated`** fires on resume.
- **`Preferences`** persists small strings across app restarts (backed by `SharedPreferences` on Android, `NSUserDefaults` on iOS).
- Unsubscribe in `OnDisappearing` to avoid leaks.
- Call `ClearDraft()` after the user intentionally saves, so stale drafts don't reappear.

For large text, consider `SecureStorage` or writing to a file via `FileSystem.AppDataDirectory` instead of `Preferences`.
